WEBVTT

1
00:00:12.734 --> 00:00:13.735
Here's your vitamins.

2
00:00:16.405 --> 00:00:17.656
[knocks on door]

3
00:00:19.241 --> 00:00:23.120
- What'd you get for supper?
- Uh... Soup.

4
00:00:23.203 --> 00:00:24.455
You always get soup.

5
00:00:30.043 --> 00:00:31.961
- [delivery person] Madam Mayor. Hey.
- Hey. Tony.

6
00:00:32.045 --> 00:00:33.714
- What's tonight?
- Uh. mushroom.

7
00:00:33.797 --> 00:00:36.216
- Mushroom? Do I like mushroom?
- Who doesn't like mushrooms?

8
00:00:36.300 --> 00:00:37.926
[Tony]
I'll be back for the tray later. ma'am.

9
00:00:38.010 --> 00:00:39.511
Okay. Thank you. Tony.

10
00:00:42.723 --> 00:00:44.141
I know you're tired of
hearing me say this.

11
00:00:44.224 --> 00:00:46.518
- but you know I'm going to.
- No. I know. Go.

12
00:00:46.602 --> 00:00:48.270
Remember. the Silo is at peace

13
00:00:48.353 --> 00:00:49.772
- because of you.
- Because of me. Mm-hmm.

14
00:00:49.855 --> 00:00:51.231
Because you came back.

15
00:00:52.024 --> 00:00:54.109
- Yeah.
- See you in the morning.

16
00:00:54.193 --> 00:00:55.235
Bye.

17
00:01:00.783 --> 00:01:01.784
Good night.

18
00:01:06.747 --> 00:01:09.416
[eerie music playing]

19
00:02:02.344 --> 00:02:03.345
[spits]

20
00:02:32.541 --> 00:02:33.667
[Camille] There you are.

21
00:02:34.626 --> 00:02:35.669
How'd you sleep?

22
00:02:35.752 --> 00:02:38.130
- [Juliette] Um. fine.
- Yeah?

23
00:02:38.213 --> 00:02:39.339
- Yeah.
- Good.

24
00:02:39.965 --> 00:02:44.219
Um. we need to go over some of the details
for the Council meeting tomorrow.

25
00:02:44.303 --> 00:02:46.430
- Okay. Mm-hmm.
- Very exciting.

26
00:02:46.513 --> 00:02:49.308
But we can do that
after your weekly in the cafeteria.

27
00:02:50.100 --> 00:02:51.435
Mm-hmm.

28
00:02:51.518 --> 00:02:53.854
I know you don't like these appearances.

29
00:02:53.937 --> 00:02:55.856
but the people need to see you.

30
00:02:56.565 --> 00:02:59.067
Yeah. The people need to see me.

31
00:02:59.985 --> 00:03:04.198
[citizens cheering. chanting]
Madam Mayor! Mayor Nichols!

32
00:03:16.460 --> 00:03:18.128
[cheering distorts]

33
00:03:29.932 --> 00:03:31.725
[fan] There she is! Juliette!

34
00:03:38.732 --> 00:03:40.692
Don't worry about them. You're good.

35
00:03:51.245 --> 00:03:54.289
Ladies. I have something
that might interest you.

36
00:03:55.040 --> 00:03:56.291
Can I see it?

37
00:03:56.875 --> 00:03:58.627
You mean can you touch it?

38
00:03:58.710 --> 00:03:59.962
No.

39
00:04:00.045 --> 00:04:01.088
How much?

40
00:04:01.171 --> 00:04:04.007
I was thinking
more along the lines of a trade.

41
00:04:09.096 --> 00:04:10.514
- What is that?
- A toy.

42
00:04:11.098 --> 00:04:13.475
We think it belonged either to her
or her brother.

43
00:04:13.559 --> 00:04:16.228
I know someone who got it
from her father's place.

44
00:04:20.858 --> 00:04:23.735
[suspenseful music playing]

45
00:04:37.332 --> 00:04:38.500
I wanna go.

46
00:04:40.085 --> 00:04:42.171
- I wanna go.
- Okay. Okay.

47
00:04:42.754 --> 00:04:44.381
[suspenseful music continues]

48
00:06:50.132 --> 00:06:52.217
[dramatic music playing]

49
00:07:40.474 --> 00:07:42.518
[dramatic music continues]

50
00:07:48.607 --> 00:07:50.109
[brakes squeal]

51
00:07:51.360 --> 00:07:54.863
[automated voice] <i>Doors opening.
Step back to allow customers to exit.</i>

52
00:07:55.614 --> 00:07:58.158
<i>When boarding.
please move to the center of the car.</i>

53
00:07:58.242 --> 00:07:59.785
[tense music playing]

54
00:08:14.967 --> 00:08:17.010
[automated voice]
<i>Step back. Doors closing.</i>

55
00:08:18.095 --> 00:08:20.722
[tense music continues]

56
00:08:34.361 --> 00:08:35.362
[person on phone] <i>Hello?</i>

57
00:08:35.445 --> 00:08:36.988
[sighs] Is that Mr. Jones?

58
00:08:37.072 --> 00:08:39.700
- [Jones] <i>Yes?</i>
- This is. uh. Congressman Daniel Keene.

59
00:08:39.782 --> 00:08:40.993
How are you today?

60
00:08:41.075 --> 00:08:42.618
[Jones] <i>I'll tell you what. Congressman.</i>

61
00:08:42.703 --> 00:08:46.623
<i>You put me on your "do not call" list.
and you got my vote next go-round.</i>

62
00:08:46.707 --> 00:08:47.708
<i>You call again.</i>

63
00:08:48.292 --> 00:08:50.752
<i>I will vote for whoever the fuck
they run against you.</i>

64
00:08:50.836 --> 00:08:52.296
- [Jones hangs up]
- You got it.

65
00:09:09.229 --> 00:09:10.230
Hi.

66
00:09:11.440 --> 00:09:12.733
You do what I said?

67
00:09:13.484 --> 00:09:14.485
What'd you say?

68
00:09:14.568 --> 00:09:17.571
I said if you didn't do what I said.
I'd punch you in the throat.

69
00:09:17.654 --> 00:09:19.907
Well. we certainly don't want that.

70
00:09:20.491 --> 00:09:23.660
Yeah. I took two trains.
two cabs. circled back...

71
00:09:23.744 --> 00:09:26.205
- [laughs]
- Got you a sweet tea.

72
00:09:27.164 --> 00:09:29.792
- Lots of ice.
- Yeah. they call it iced tea here.

73
00:09:30.626 --> 00:09:33.170
Well. I'm not from here. Neither are you.

74
00:09:38.509 --> 00:09:40.010
What's going on. Charles?

75
00:09:41.178 --> 00:09:43.263
You're off post. but you're not on leave.

76
00:09:43.347 --> 00:09:44.890
Shouldn't you be in uniform?

77
00:09:44.973 --> 00:09:47.101
Shouldn't you be on a phone
sucking dick for money?

78
00:09:48.852 --> 00:09:50.020
Wow.

79
00:09:51.230 --> 00:09:54.108
You've been in the Navy too long.
If Mom and Dad were alive right now...

80
00:09:54.191 --> 00:09:55.859
They'd be clawing frantically...

81
00:09:55.943 --> 00:09:57.528
[both] ...to get out of their coffins.

82
00:10:02.658 --> 00:10:04.118
Why'd you think it was a date?

83
00:10:05.744 --> 00:10:08.455
- What? Huh?
- [stammers. laughs] That reporter.

84
00:10:09.331 --> 00:10:10.541
Helen Drew.

85
00:10:11.208 --> 00:10:13.210
- How do you...
- She said you gave her a Pez.

86
00:10:14.795 --> 00:10:16.672
- I thought it was funny.
- Uh-huh. was it?

87
00:10:18.632 --> 00:10:22.386
She also said you managed to work
New Orleans into the conversation.

88
00:10:23.053 --> 00:10:24.138
Smooth.

89
00:10:25.556 --> 00:10:28.392
She was dismissive of the Corps.
I thought I'd set her straight.

90
00:10:28.475 --> 00:10:30.894
New Orleans was a big deal.
I was a big part of it.

91
00:10:30.978 --> 00:10:32.438
We did things no one
had thought of before...

92
00:10:32.521 --> 00:10:34.606
Oh. that's right. I forgot.
You invented drills.

93
00:10:34.690 --> 00:10:36.150
How do you know what we said?

94
00:10:38.193 --> 00:10:39.653
She's working on a story.

95
00:10:39.736 --> 00:10:43.115
I couldn't help her.
I said she should talk to you.

96
00:10:43.198 --> 00:10:45.451
Told her you might not
be completely useless.

97
00:10:46.493 --> 00:10:48.871
If you got on Thurman's Iran Committee.

98
00:10:50.581 --> 00:10:51.915
[chuckling] Um...

99
00:10:51.999 --> 00:10:53.167
Everyone wants on that.

100
00:10:53.250 --> 00:10:55.002
- Well. doesn't she owe you?
- For what?

101
00:10:55.085 --> 00:10:56.670
You said good things about her.

102
00:10:56.753 --> 00:10:58.422
I was running for congress.
She's a senator.

103
00:10:58.505 --> 00:11:00.507
We both represent the good people
of the Peach State.

104
00:11:00.591 --> 00:11:02.050
Of course I said good things about her.

105
00:11:02.134 --> 00:11:04.011
But I'd be surprised
if she even knows my name.

106
00:11:04.094 --> 00:11:05.637
Why wouldn't she?

107
00:11:06.638 --> 00:11:09.349
Well. we have this thing in America.
It's called the party system.

108
00:11:09.433 --> 00:11:10.559
We're not in the same one.

109
00:11:10.642 --> 00:11:12.853
Look. you should really try
and get on that committee.

110
00:11:14.438 --> 00:11:15.564
What's going on?

111
00:11:16.398 --> 00:11:19.151
Have you been assigned
to whatever we got planned?

112
00:11:19.234 --> 00:11:22.362
Even if I was.
I couldn't tell you. civilian swine.

113
00:11:22.446 --> 00:11:24.072
I was in the Army.

114
00:11:24.156 --> 00:11:25.199
You were an engineer.

115
00:11:25.282 --> 00:11:26.575
And now I'm in congress.

116
00:11:26.658 --> 00:11:29.953
I think I'm allowed to know
if my little sister is gonna bomb Iran.

117
00:11:32.289 --> 00:11:33.582
Gotta go.

118
00:11:36.084 --> 00:11:39.671
I did the whole switching cabs
and trains thing for two minutes with you?

119
00:11:39.755 --> 00:11:41.381
Well. I'm sorry. I couldn't take a chance

120
00:11:41.465 --> 00:11:43.467
- talking on the phone.
- Tell me what the hell is going on.

121
00:11:43.550 --> 00:11:45.344
I am telling you.

122
00:11:45.427 --> 00:11:48.806
Get on that committee.
and tell the reporter what you can.

123
00:11:55.104 --> 00:11:56.313
You forgot something.

124
00:12:15.290 --> 00:12:17.876
[Bernard] After all I've done. sacrificed.

125
00:12:17.960 --> 00:12:20.295
to find out it never really mattered.

126
00:12:20.379 --> 00:12:21.505
Maybe not.

127
00:12:21.588 --> 00:12:22.965
What do you mean?

128
00:12:24.049 --> 00:12:26.426
[gasps. panting]

129
00:12:36.603 --> 00:12:38.105
- [Camille] Hey.
- [Juliette] Hi.

130
00:12:38.188 --> 00:12:39.773
- [Camille] What happened?
- I. uh...

131
00:12:39.857 --> 00:12:43.152
[breathes heavily] I had a... a dream.

132
00:12:43.235 --> 00:12:45.446
- I-I-I don't know. Yeah. I-I. uh...
- [Camille] A dream?

133
00:12:46.321 --> 00:12:47.948
I'm outside the air lock...

134
00:12:48.031 --> 00:12:50.576
[stammers] ...um.
with Bernard and we're... [sighs]

135
00:12:50.659 --> 00:12:53.954
[stammering]
We're outside the air lock and...

136
00:12:54.037 --> 00:12:55.747
- Juliette.
- I-I don't know. I. um...

137
00:12:55.831 --> 00:12:58.167
- Hey. [stammers]
- [Juliette] No. There's something...

138
00:13:00.586 --> 00:13:02.004
There's something I have to do.

139
00:13:02.087 --> 00:13:03.422
- I have to do something.
- What do you have to do?

140
00:13:03.505 --> 00:13:05.757
I don't know. I have to... I can't. I...

141
00:13:06.633 --> 00:13:09.636
I don't know. I don't know.
but he was right there. [stammers]

142
00:13:09.720 --> 00:13:11.847
- [breathing heavily]
- Okay. stop. Stop.

143
00:13:13.098 --> 00:13:14.349
Let's do the exercise.

144
00:13:14.433 --> 00:13:16.268
[Juliette sighs]
If I could only talk to Bernard.

145
00:13:16.351 --> 00:13:18.604
- [Camille] That's not possible.
- I know. I know.

146
00:13:18.687 --> 00:13:20.063
- Look at me.
- Okay.

147
00:13:20.147 --> 00:13:22.024
- Match my breathing. Slow.
- [exhales heavily]

148
00:13:22.649 --> 00:13:24.401
In for three seconds. Hold.

149
00:13:24.485 --> 00:13:26.195
- And out.
- [exhales]

150
00:13:26.278 --> 00:13:28.155
Good. Good. One more time.

151
00:13:28.989 --> 00:13:30.574
In for three seconds.

152
00:13:32.451 --> 00:13:34.453
- [breathing deeply]
- <i>Keep breathing. Good.</i>

153
00:13:34.995 --> 00:13:36.538
- <i>Good. One more time.</i>
- [exhales sharply]

154
00:13:37.790 --> 00:13:41.627
<i>Good. You're okay now.
Just keep breathing. keep breathing.</i>

155
00:13:58.727 --> 00:14:00.562
[Sims] You were in there
for three minutes.

156
00:14:02.564 --> 00:14:05.818
Three minutes in a box of fire
before the door would open

157
00:14:06.401 --> 00:14:08.278
and your friends could get you out.

158
00:14:10.239 --> 00:14:13.325
All oxygen was gone 30 seconds in.

159
00:14:15.369 --> 00:14:18.372
Your suit.
it wasn't a regular cleaning suit.

160
00:14:19.081 --> 00:14:20.666
It was insulated.

161
00:14:21.291 --> 00:14:22.459
It protected you.

162
00:14:25.754 --> 00:14:27.673
Bernard wasn't so lucky.

163
00:14:28.549 --> 00:14:32.678
<i>The flames melted holes in his suit.
and the poison got in.</i>

164
00:14:34.221 --> 00:14:36.598
<i>We couldn't take a chance
with a farm burial.</i>

165
00:14:36.682 --> 00:14:38.600
<i>The stairs were evacuated.</i>

166
00:14:38.684 --> 00:14:41.437
<i>No one was allowed into the central shaft.</i>

167
00:14:42.896 --> 00:14:48.068
<i>It took six porters six hours
to get him down to the incinerator.</i>

168
00:14:50.487 --> 00:14:53.323
[machine clanking. whirring]

169
00:15:03.292 --> 00:15:04.877
Bernard can't help you.

170
00:15:08.380 --> 00:15:10.257
Because I watched him burn.

171
00:15:17.014 --> 00:15:19.850
My wife says you remember something
about him.

172
00:15:21.059 --> 00:15:24.104
There's something you have to do.

173
00:15:25.939 --> 00:15:27.900
No. I can't. I can't remember.

174
00:15:28.650 --> 00:15:31.612
I hope you get more of your memory back.

175
00:15:32.946 --> 00:15:34.281
I really do.

176
00:15:38.994 --> 00:15:44.500
I particularly hope you remember why
you held my wife and son hostage

177
00:15:44.583 --> 00:15:45.793
at gunpoint.

178
00:15:53.342 --> 00:15:54.426
Who are you?

179
00:15:57.763 --> 00:16:01.433
Who are you? Hmm?

180
00:16:03.852 --> 00:16:05.437
I'm Robert Sims.

181
00:16:07.147 --> 00:16:10.275
- I'm the Judge of the Silo...
- No. no. no. no. no. I know. I know.

182
00:16:10.359 --> 00:16:11.485
You tell me that.

183
00:16:12.194 --> 00:16:13.529
I don't know you.

184
00:16:14.363 --> 00:16:17.866
I don't know you.
I don't know anyone. right?

185
00:16:18.909 --> 00:16:22.412
I look at myself in the mirror. and I
don't even know who's looking back at me.

186
00:16:22.913 --> 00:16:23.914
And...

187
00:16:25.415 --> 00:16:29.253
I thought. maybe...
maybe I had remembered something.

188
00:16:30.212 --> 00:16:31.547
But it's gone.

189
00:16:32.881 --> 00:16:35.634
And. what. you're gonna tell me
it's a dream? It's a dream?

190
00:16:37.386 --> 00:16:38.929
[whispers] I don't know.

191
00:16:51.775 --> 00:16:53.694
Okay. and pull up that previous file.

192
00:16:55.195 --> 00:16:56.321
Yeah. there.

193
00:16:56.947 --> 00:16:58.574
I'm gonna need all of those removed.

194
00:16:58.657 --> 00:16:59.908
Okay.

195
00:17:04.913 --> 00:17:06.081
What did you tell her?

196
00:17:07.374 --> 00:17:09.293
That Bernard died from the poison.

197
00:17:09.375 --> 00:17:10.626
- [sighs]
- [groans]

198
00:17:12.629 --> 00:17:14.339
[groaning]

199
00:17:15.466 --> 00:17:17.009
[groaning]

200
00:17:43.702 --> 00:17:44.703
Thanks.

201
00:17:44.787 --> 00:17:48.040
Well. if it isn't the hero of New Orleans.

202
00:17:48.123 --> 00:17:50.000
A hero of New Orleans.

203
00:17:50.083 --> 00:17:52.419
There were 500 Army engineers
on that project.

204
00:17:52.503 --> 00:17:54.505
But Congressman Keene was key. right?

205
00:17:54.588 --> 00:17:58.217
You came up with the idea
of replacing levees with tunnels.

206
00:17:58.300 --> 00:18:03.806
and you invented some kind of drill
that didn't disturb the soil above. right?

207
00:18:04.473 --> 00:18:06.600
Sounds like you read
my campaign literature. [chuckles]

208
00:18:06.683 --> 00:18:07.935
Your campaign was well-written.

209
00:18:08.018 --> 00:18:10.354
Anna is the writer in our family.

210
00:18:10.437 --> 00:18:13.232
[Anna] Oh. not press releases.
Legislation. I write bills.

211
00:18:13.315 --> 00:18:15.025
She tidies them up.

212
00:18:15.109 --> 00:18:17.820
If they start accepting them in crayon.
she won't need me.

213
00:18:17.903 --> 00:18:19.738
What can I do for you today. Congressman?

214
00:18:19.822 --> 00:18:24.451
Um. well. is there gonna be
retaliation against Iran?

215
00:18:24.535 --> 00:18:27.663
They set off a dirty bomb
in our nation's capital.

216
00:18:27.746 --> 00:18:29.498
of course there's going to be
a retaliation.

217
00:18:30.249 --> 00:18:32.209
I'd like to be assigned
to the Iran Committee.

218
00:18:33.085 --> 00:18:35.254
Son. there's a waiting list
for the waiting list.

219
00:18:35.337 --> 00:18:36.922
I'd like to jump the line.

220
00:18:37.005 --> 00:18:39.049
All right. give me your elevator pitch.

221
00:18:42.803 --> 00:18:43.929
Um.

222
00:18:45.180 --> 00:18:49.435
my sister Charlotte Keene
is a Naval aviator attached to the <i>Nimitz</i>.

223
00:18:49.518 --> 00:18:52.187
Any retaliatory mission
is gonna be carrier-based.

224
00:18:52.271 --> 00:18:53.897
The <i>Nimitz</i> is fresh off a refurb.

225
00:18:53.981 --> 00:18:55.649
Charlotte flies an F-35.

226
00:18:55.732 --> 00:18:57.651
Her squadron's flown
several missions in theater.

227
00:18:58.819 --> 00:19:00.154
That's a good pitch.

228
00:19:00.737 --> 00:19:02.322
I'll try to get you on.

229
00:19:03.365 --> 00:19:06.660
Your last campaign slogan was. uh. Yoda.

230
00:19:06.743 --> 00:19:08.579
"Don't try. Do."

231
00:19:08.662 --> 00:19:11.165
You might wanna dial it down
a little bit. Congressman.

232
00:19:11.248 --> 00:19:13.792
And I would. except. you know.
Charlotte's my only family.

233
00:19:13.876 --> 00:19:16.295
and I'd just love to know
what we're doing and why.

234
00:19:16.378 --> 00:19:18.088
And I will see what I can do.

235
00:19:20.132 --> 00:19:21.300
Anna.

236
00:19:31.935 --> 00:19:33.771
[sighs] I blew it. didn't I?

237
00:19:34.396 --> 00:19:37.858
Oh. well. she didn't throw anything.
so not too bad.

238
00:19:38.609 --> 00:19:40.778
- [sighs]
- Thanks for saving New Orleans.

239
00:19:42.112 --> 00:19:43.113
[scoffs]

240
00:19:45.741 --> 00:19:47.159
[Thurman] His sister.

241
00:19:48.076 --> 00:19:49.787
- What is her name?
- Charlotte Keene.

242
00:19:49.870 --> 00:19:52.498
She flies an F-35 off the <i>Nimitz</i>.

243
00:19:52.581 --> 00:19:55.250
[Sims] We're here today
in the Mids cafeteria

244
00:19:55.334 --> 00:19:56.543
because of one man.

245
00:19:57.377 --> 00:19:59.505
- Bernard Holland.
- [citizens murmuring]

246
00:19:59.588 --> 00:20:01.965
I worked with Bernard for ten years.

247
00:20:03.342 --> 00:20:06.261
And all that time. I never knew his mind.

248
00:20:06.929 --> 00:20:10.933
I knew the position and authority
he claimed weren't in the Pact.

249
00:20:11.517 --> 00:20:16.522
But Bernard assured me it was tradition
and had been since the beginning.

250
00:20:16.605 --> 00:20:20.692
My predecessors had gone along with it.
and so did I.

251
00:20:20.776 --> 00:20:22.945
So did my wife. Camille.

252
00:20:24.404 --> 00:20:25.906
So did we all.

253
00:20:27.074 --> 00:20:28.951
But when rebellion came.

254
00:20:29.034 --> 00:20:31.995
we debated long and hard. my wife and I.

255
00:20:32.079 --> 00:20:33.622
And finally we felt.

256
00:20:34.665 --> 00:20:36.291
as so many of us did.

257
00:20:36.375 --> 00:20:39.169
- that it was time for change.
- [citizens] Yeah.

258
00:20:39.253 --> 00:20:41.630
- For transparency.
- [citizens] Right!

259
00:20:41.713 --> 00:20:42.965
For truth.

260
00:20:43.048 --> 00:20:44.383
[citizens applauding]

261
00:20:44.466 --> 00:20:48.262
[Sims] But truth does not come
without costs.

262
00:20:48.846 --> 00:20:51.390
These last three months
have been transformative

263
00:20:51.473 --> 00:20:53.058
in so many ways.

264
00:20:53.892 --> 00:20:58.981
Sheriff Paul Billings is rewriting
portions of the Pact that need revising.

265
00:20:59.064 --> 00:21:04.319
Most of the cameras Bernard installed
throughout the Silo have been removed.

266
00:21:04.403 --> 00:21:09.032
leaving only the ones necessary
for public safety and security.

267
00:21:09.116 --> 00:21:14.538
And most important of all.
there is now this council.

268
00:21:14.621 --> 00:21:18.459
composed of level reps
and department heads.

269
00:21:24.590 --> 00:21:27.009
Change has happened. Change has happened.

270
00:21:28.093 --> 00:21:29.219
And now.

271
00:21:29.303 --> 00:21:32.139
it is my privilege to introduce

272
00:21:32.222 --> 00:21:36.602
the only person sent out to clean
ever to return.

273
00:21:37.394 --> 00:21:42.733
And the only person to be sworn in
while lying in a hospital bed.

274
00:21:43.776 --> 00:21:46.987
Our mayor. Juliette Nichols.

275
00:21:47.613 --> 00:21:50.949
[cheering]

276
00:21:57.122 --> 00:21:58.874
[cheering. whistling]

277
00:22:03.212 --> 00:22:04.254
Thank you.

278
00:22:04.338 --> 00:22:05.923
Um.

279
00:22:06.006 --> 00:22:12.513
I. uh. now declare the Silo's
first Council meeting. um. open.

280
00:22:12.596 --> 00:22:15.224
- [bangs gavel]
- [citizens applauding. cheering]

281
00:22:16.391 --> 00:22:18.143
- Yeah?
- [Anna] Thanks.

282
00:22:18.227 --> 00:22:20.145
Congressman. I wasn't sure I'd catch you.

283
00:22:20.646 --> 00:22:24.483
Hey. Um. did I get on the Iran Committee?

284
00:22:24.566 --> 00:22:27.486
The senator had me contact
an old friend at JSOC.

285
00:22:27.569 --> 00:22:29.571
I asked him to track your sister.

286
00:22:30.697 --> 00:22:33.826
You were right. She is slated to fly
in the Iran operation.

287
00:22:33.909 --> 00:22:36.870
[inhales sharply] Um. when?

288
00:22:36.954 --> 00:22:38.288
Tonight.

289
00:22:39.873 --> 00:22:40.874
[sighs]

290
00:23:00.519 --> 00:23:02.020
[pilot 1] <i>Coming up on the</i> McCain<i>.</i>

291
00:23:06.942 --> 00:23:08.694
I have visual at 9:00.

292
00:23:18.579 --> 00:23:20.664
[pilot 1]
<i>Okay. folks. Let's climb to 50.000.</i>

293
00:23:20.747 --> 00:23:24.460
Seventy-five klicks till target.
then zoom and boom back to Uncle Chester.

294
00:23:24.543 --> 00:23:26.003
[Charlotte] Raider Two. copy.

295
00:23:26.086 --> 00:23:28.172
- [pilot 2] <i>Three. copy.</i>
- [pilot 3] <i>Four. copy.</i>

296
00:23:51.320 --> 00:23:53.071
<i>Y'all seeing this cloud up ahead?</i>

297
00:23:53.155 --> 00:23:56.200
[navigation system beeping]

298
00:23:56.283 --> 00:23:58.786
What the fuck's a cloud doing
at 50.000 feet?

299
00:24:06.210 --> 00:24:07.628
[beeping continues]

300
00:24:10.839 --> 00:24:12.174
[pilot 2] <i>Look at the Tomahawks.</i>

301
00:24:13.967 --> 00:24:16.929
<i>What the fuck?
We're 500 klicks from target.</i>

302
00:24:19.098 --> 00:24:21.475
[pilot 3] <i>Raider Four. I've got something
weird on my instrument panel.</i>

303
00:24:22.392 --> 00:24:24.436
[pilot 1] <i>Raider One. Looks like oil.</i>

304
00:24:24.520 --> 00:24:26.522
[pilot 2] <i>Raider Three.
Yeah. I've got it too.</i>

305
00:24:27.856 --> 00:24:28.982
[pilot 1] <i>What is it?</i>

306
00:24:29.066 --> 00:24:30.567
[beeping continues]

307
00:24:33.403 --> 00:24:36.990
[alarm system beeping rapidly]

308
00:24:37.074 --> 00:24:38.534
[pilot 2] <i>Raider One. I'm armed!</i>

309
00:24:39.159 --> 00:24:40.410
<i>I-I can't...</i>

310
00:24:41.453 --> 00:24:42.454
<i>Fuck!</i>

311
00:24:54.133 --> 00:24:56.885
Mayday. Mayday. Mayday!
Drone controls are going down!

312
00:25:08.856 --> 00:25:09.857
Here.

313
00:25:12.568 --> 00:25:14.278
[no audible dialogue on TV]

314
00:25:25.205 --> 00:25:26.415
[Anna] Daniel?

315
00:25:36.383 --> 00:25:38.385
That was my friend from JSOC.

316
00:25:38.469 --> 00:25:41.138
Your sister's squadron
wasn't hitting any of the targets

317
00:25:41.221 --> 00:25:43.474
they're talking about on TV.

318
00:25:43.557 --> 00:25:48.020
They were on a mission
to a facility in the mountains.

319
00:25:48.771 --> 00:25:50.689
Charlotte's plane went down.

320
00:25:51.315 --> 00:25:54.651
but a rescue team out of Turkmenistan
picked her up.

321
00:25:55.402 --> 00:25:56.445
She's alive.

322
00:25:57.946 --> 00:25:59.990
[stammers] She's alive?

323
00:26:00.073 --> 00:26:01.116
[stammers]

324
00:26:03.577 --> 00:26:04.578
[sniffs]

325
00:26:05.746 --> 00:26:08.123
Harwood. Head of Mines.

326
00:26:08.207 --> 00:26:09.583
I don't know what you want me...

327
00:26:09.666 --> 00:26:11.710
Just give us a status report. Ed.

328
00:26:13.003 --> 00:26:14.046
We're miners.

329
00:26:14.129 --> 00:26:15.255
We're mining.

330
00:26:15.339 --> 00:26:17.049
There was an accident yesterday?

331
00:26:18.217 --> 00:26:20.928
I don't know how much
of an accident it was. but yeah.

332
00:26:21.011 --> 00:26:22.137
There was a...

333
00:26:22.221 --> 00:26:26.225
There was a collapse
in the B-92 spur off subshaft David.

334
00:26:26.308 --> 00:26:28.519
Seven were trapped. We got 'em out.

335
00:26:28.602 --> 00:26:29.603
Am I done?

336
00:26:29.686 --> 00:26:32.731
Sorry. You don't know
how much of an accident it was?

337
00:26:33.899 --> 00:26:35.025
[sighs]

338
00:26:35.109 --> 00:26:39.029
Look. everyone says it's a mystery
how old the Silo is.

339
00:26:39.113 --> 00:26:40.489
Not to us.

340
00:26:40.572 --> 00:26:44.535
The number of shafts and tunnels we got.
it's been here at least 300 years.

341
00:26:45.160 --> 00:26:48.580
Three hundred years of shafts
and tunnels going this way and that.

342
00:26:48.664 --> 00:26:51.500
up and down. sideways. but never out.

343
00:26:52.334 --> 00:26:54.545
At least not more than 200 feet.

344
00:26:55.254 --> 00:26:56.463
Why?

345
00:26:56.547 --> 00:26:58.841
Because it's in the Pact.

346
00:26:59.925 --> 00:27:04.346
Which means you got 300 years of tunnels
and shafts doubling back on each other.

347
00:27:04.930 --> 00:27:07.766
Add to that the effects of the bomb
set off by the rebels.

348
00:27:07.850 --> 00:27:10.018
- [citizens murmuring]
- [Ed] I'm not taking sides.

349
00:27:10.102 --> 00:27:11.145
What's done is done.

350
00:27:11.228 --> 00:27:13.021
I'm just stating a fact.

351
00:27:14.273 --> 00:27:18.110
So it's not an accident
the tunnel collapsed.

352
00:27:18.694 --> 00:27:21.989
It's a fucking miracle
it doesn't happen every week.

353
00:27:23.031 --> 00:27:24.241
Why. um...

354
00:27:25.868 --> 00:27:28.745
Why does the Pact limit
how far out they can go?

355
00:27:28.829 --> 00:27:29.872
[Ed] Yeah. fuck knows.

356
00:27:31.081 --> 00:27:32.082
[Juliette] Okay.

357
00:27:32.708 --> 00:27:36.253
Okay. so maybe that's something
that we can look into.

358
00:27:37.254 --> 00:27:38.505
- We will do that.
- Yeah?

359
00:27:41.341 --> 00:27:45.053
My name is Orla Kent.
and I am shadow to the head of Supply.

360
00:27:45.137 --> 00:27:48.056
Carla McLain asked me
to come represent her here today...

361
00:27:48.140 --> 00:27:50.058
[Ed groans] How... [scoffs]

362
00:27:50.684 --> 00:27:52.019
How old are you?

363
00:27:53.145 --> 00:27:54.605
Twenty-six.

364
00:27:54.688 --> 00:27:55.773
Twenty-six?

365
00:27:56.356 --> 00:27:58.108
I've got boots older than that.

366
00:27:58.192 --> 00:28:00.319
[citizens chuckling]

367
00:28:01.653 --> 00:28:03.071
So do I. Mr. Harwood.

368
00:28:03.697 --> 00:28:05.657
They're my Aunt Doreen's boots.

369
00:28:05.741 --> 00:28:09.828
She worked Supply-side 40 years.
as did my mother and father.

370
00:28:10.412 --> 00:28:11.705
I grew up in the bays.

371
00:28:11.789 --> 00:28:14.249
Started pulling boxes
on the high-line at ten.

372
00:28:14.333 --> 00:28:15.542
[Ed] Yeah. yeah.

373
00:28:15.626 --> 00:28:18.545
All I'm saying is.
if I had to come here. so should Carla.

374
00:28:18.629 --> 00:28:21.256
Carla McLain understands
how important today is.

375
00:28:21.340 --> 00:28:23.967
but she also remains set on retiring.

376
00:28:24.051 --> 00:28:25.344
And she wanted me here

377
00:28:25.427 --> 00:28:28.263
as I'll be the one giving these reports
in the future.

378
00:28:28.347 --> 00:28:29.932
Thank you. That's great.

379
00:28:30.015 --> 00:28:32.351
So now we've cleared that up. your report.

380
00:28:33.018 --> 00:28:34.186
[Orla] Thank you.

381
00:28:34.269 --> 00:28:36.855
Because of production shutdowns
during the rebellion.

382
00:28:36.939 --> 00:28:38.774
there were many shortages right after.

383
00:28:38.857 --> 00:28:40.818
But we worked with the suppliers.

384
00:28:40.901 --> 00:28:44.029
released a prudent amount
from reserves and Critical Supply.

385
00:28:44.113 --> 00:28:46.281
and citizens reduced their usage.

386
00:28:46.365 --> 00:28:49.785
We are now back
to pre-rebellion levels in all sectors.

387
00:28:49.868 --> 00:28:52.996
Bottom line. we are good in Supply.

388
00:28:53.080 --> 00:28:54.665
[citizens applauding]

389
00:28:56.083 --> 00:28:57.417
[Martha] <i>You wanted the truth.</i>

390
00:28:58.627 --> 00:29:00.838
{\an8}<i>They're good in Supply.</i>

391
00:29:00.921 --> 00:29:02.172
[Camille] Mr. Knox.

392
00:29:04.341 --> 00:29:07.094
[Knox] Ed. I-I think I speak
for everyone here when I say.

393
00:29:07.177 --> 00:29:09.346
what the hell are you complaining about?

394
00:29:09.429 --> 00:29:11.098
I came up from 144.

395
00:29:11.181 --> 00:29:12.558
I had to be hauled up the gap

396
00:29:12.641 --> 00:29:15.644
by a couple of skinny bastards
I was sure were gonna drop my ass.

397
00:29:15.727 --> 00:29:17.354
- [citizens chuckling]
- [Knox] Anyway.

398
00:29:18.522 --> 00:29:21.608
the generator is humming along
just fine thanks to you. Juliette...

399
00:29:21.692 --> 00:29:24.069
uh. Madam Mayor.

400
00:29:24.736 --> 00:29:26.155
and your fix from before.

401
00:29:26.947 --> 00:29:30.367
The only other thing to report has to do
with what we call the digger void.

402
00:29:30.451 --> 00:29:33.328
When word of it got out.
people... [stammers]

403
00:29:33.412 --> 00:29:37.916
...mostly young idiots.
came down for a look-see

404
00:29:38.000 --> 00:29:39.793
and quite a few had to be rescued.

405
00:29:40.711 --> 00:29:44.006
Martha Walker has taken it upon herself
to seal off the access.

406
00:29:44.089 --> 00:29:46.175
Everything we could use from there was...

407
00:29:46.258 --> 00:29:47.968
was taken out a long time ago.

408
00:29:48.969 --> 00:29:51.597
Anyway. that's all I got.

409
00:29:51.680 --> 00:29:52.681
[Camille] Thank you.

410
00:29:55.058 --> 00:29:56.101
Sheriff?

411
00:29:57.811 --> 00:29:59.646
[inhales sharply. clears throat]

412
00:30:02.775 --> 00:30:05.944
Um. Sheriff Paul Billings.

413
00:30:06.028 --> 00:30:07.196
Not much to report.

414
00:30:07.279 --> 00:30:08.947
I've been working on the Pact.

415
00:30:09.031 --> 00:30:10.115
Crime is down.

416
00:30:10.199 --> 00:30:11.450
I think that's it.

417
00:30:11.533 --> 00:30:13.952
Any progress on our two fugitives?

418
00:30:14.995 --> 00:30:19.249
Uh. there've been sightings of Kennedy.
but when we get there. he's gone.

419
00:30:19.333 --> 00:30:20.667
if he was there at all.

420
00:30:21.168 --> 00:30:22.920
Nothing on Lukas Kyle.

421
00:30:23.003 --> 00:30:27.382
We think he may have died in the rebellion
and his body was misidentified.

422
00:30:27.466 --> 00:30:30.344
We only found Rick Amundsen two weeks ago.

423
00:30:30.427 --> 00:30:31.970
What about the Outsiders?

424
00:30:34.765 --> 00:30:37.184
[Paul] They do their stunts.
and by the time we get there.

425
00:30:37.267 --> 00:30:38.435
they've disappeared.

426
00:30:39.103 --> 00:30:40.354
Any idea who they are?

427
00:30:41.146 --> 00:30:43.690
Other than followers of Kennedy? No.

428
00:30:44.483 --> 00:30:45.734
They wear masks.

429
00:30:51.031 --> 00:30:52.282
[Knox] Madam Mayor.

430
00:30:54.076 --> 00:30:55.285
[Camille] It's okay. Jerry.

431
00:30:55.828 --> 00:30:56.912
Mr. Knox.

432
00:30:57.955 --> 00:30:59.998
I just wanted to ask about your memory.

433
00:31:00.541 --> 00:31:02.167
Anything coming back?

434
00:31:02.251 --> 00:31:04.545
- Getting better every day.
- Yeah.

435
00:31:05.754 --> 00:31:09.299
So nothing more
about what it was like outside?

436
00:31:09.967 --> 00:31:12.469
No. just what we've seen. Mmm.

437
00:31:13.303 --> 00:31:15.180
Do you remember me? Do...

438
00:31:15.264 --> 00:31:16.974
- Do you know who I am?
- Yeah. of course she does.

439
00:31:17.057 --> 00:31:19.435
- You're head of Mechanical. right?
- That's right.

440
00:31:25.023 --> 00:31:27.443
Your daughter still down in Supply?

441
00:31:27.526 --> 00:31:28.652
Not for long.

442
00:31:28.735 --> 00:31:30.821
Hoping she comes back up soon.

443
00:31:30.904 --> 00:31:32.406
She's at home in the mines.

444
00:31:32.906 --> 00:31:35.325
She doesn't much like working
for a teenager.

445
00:31:35.409 --> 00:31:36.410
[laughing]

446
00:31:36.493 --> 00:31:39.913
Your daughter was the same age I am.
Mr. Harwood. when she became shadow

447
00:31:39.997 --> 00:31:41.039
to the head of Supply.

448
00:31:41.123 --> 00:31:42.541
Oh. I know that.

449
00:31:43.292 --> 00:31:46.462
It's just...
I know what Glenda's capable of.

450
00:31:46.545 --> 00:31:48.630
What is she capable of. Mr. Harwood?

451
00:31:49.298 --> 00:31:50.924
Excuse me. what?

452
00:31:51.842 --> 00:31:53.177
Just a question.

453
00:31:53.719 --> 00:31:54.720
I got another.

454
00:31:57.347 --> 00:32:01.059
When was the last time you swung a pick
or shoveled ore?

455
00:32:02.144 --> 00:32:03.854
See. I still haul crates.

456
00:32:03.937 --> 00:32:06.356
Ow. You're hurting me.

457
00:32:06.940 --> 00:32:10.110
Please don't tell me we have a problem
first day of the Council.

458
00:32:10.194 --> 00:32:11.195
[Ed] Not at all.

459
00:32:16.992 --> 00:32:18.243
What was that about?

460
00:32:22.539 --> 00:32:26.043
I guess some people
just don't like change.

461
00:32:29.171 --> 00:32:31.423
[grinding]

462
00:32:51.860 --> 00:32:53.612
Great progress. right?

463
00:32:53.695 --> 00:32:54.738
Yeah.

464
00:32:56.115 --> 00:32:58.659
Yeah. You've made amazing progress.

465
00:32:58.742 --> 00:32:59.743
Thank you.

466
00:33:00.702 --> 00:33:03.247
So. you'll notice
several of the work-arounds

467
00:33:03.330 --> 00:33:05.165
violate certain rules in the Pact.

468
00:33:05.249 --> 00:33:08.168
Um. but those violations
were deemed necessary

469
00:33:08.252 --> 00:33:09.670
due to present circumstances.

470
00:33:09.753 --> 00:33:11.755
And several of those rules
are being considered

471
00:33:11.839 --> 00:33:13.549
for possible permanent changes.

472
00:33:13.632 --> 00:33:14.800
Isn't that right. Sheriff?

473
00:33:15.592 --> 00:33:16.635
Yep.

474
00:33:17.511 --> 00:33:19.054
- [Camille] Should we go up?
- [Juliette] Yeah.

475
00:33:25.102 --> 00:33:27.187
Shirley is in charge of reconstruction.

476
00:33:29.440 --> 00:33:30.858
You remember Shirley. right?

477
00:33:31.442 --> 00:33:32.985
Yeah. go ahead.

478
00:33:33.068 --> 00:33:34.069
[Juliette] Yeah. uh...

479
00:33:34.153 --> 00:33:37.364
You were at my first meet and greet
in the cafeteria. right?

480
00:33:37.448 --> 00:33:39.741
[Camille] That's right.
Your first day out of hospital.

481
00:33:41.076 --> 00:33:44.163
Uh. well. I'm. uh...
I'm sorry it's taken me this long to...

482
00:33:44.705 --> 00:33:46.373
to get down here
and see what you've been doing.

483
00:33:46.457 --> 00:33:49.209
So. I just want to say thank you
for all the hard work.

484
00:33:51.170 --> 00:33:52.379
Better get back to it.

485
00:33:52.463 --> 00:33:54.214
[Juliette] Okay. Of course.

486
00:34:04.933 --> 00:34:06.935
Oh. Is that where my dad died?

487
00:34:12.107 --> 00:34:15.486
I... I heard that his sacrifice
guaranteed the success of the rebellion?

488
00:34:19.906 --> 00:34:22.367
There wasn't supposed to be any sacrifice.

489
00:34:23.410 --> 00:34:27.039
We made sure the stairs were empty.
but the. uh...

490
00:34:28.123 --> 00:34:30.667
the device was supposed to go off
on a timer.

491
00:34:30.751 --> 00:34:32.419
but we lost the timer.

492
00:34:32.502 --> 00:34:35.672
And then... [stammers]
...Dr. Pete. he insisted on staying.

493
00:34:35.756 --> 00:34:37.424
Sorry. What's-What's your name?

494
00:34:40.969 --> 00:34:42.346
I-I'm Hank. ma'am.

495
00:34:42.428 --> 00:34:44.473
[stammers] Deputy Hank Murphy.

496
00:34:44.556 --> 00:34:47.434
Deputy Hank. I...
I really don't blame anyone.

497
00:34:48.102 --> 00:34:51.146
- Except for Bernard. of course.
- Yeah. Of course. Bernard.

498
00:34:51.772 --> 00:34:53.440
Well. Lunch is waiting.

499
00:34:53.524 --> 00:34:54.774
Oh. Okay.

500
00:35:46.243 --> 00:35:47.536
[raider] Wait. Wait. stop!

501
00:35:47.619 --> 00:35:48.954
[both grunt]

502
00:35:50.289 --> 00:35:51.415
- [grunts]
- [screams]

503
00:35:52.499 --> 00:35:54.626
[raider grunting]

504
00:35:54.710 --> 00:35:55.752
[grunts]

505
00:35:56.837 --> 00:35:58.297
Okay. [grunts]

506
00:35:58.380 --> 00:35:59.423
Okay. okay. [grunts]

507
00:36:03.677 --> 00:36:04.845
[grunts]

508
00:36:12.686 --> 00:36:14.646
I don't know how you can be like that.

509
00:36:16.190 --> 00:36:17.316
Be like what?

510
00:36:17.399 --> 00:36:20.944
Like. "Yes. Madam." "No. Madam."
It's bullshit!

511
00:36:21.028 --> 00:36:23.238
Shirl. I don't know what I'm meant to do.

512
00:36:23.322 --> 00:36:25.699
Rub it in her face
that she doesn't remember us?

513
00:36:26.408 --> 00:36:27.451
Her name is Jules.

514
00:36:27.534 --> 00:36:29.161
She's a Mechanical. She doesn't...

515
00:36:29.828 --> 00:36:33.332
She... She wouldn't be caught dead
in a dress for fuck's sake.

516
00:36:33.415 --> 00:36:35.667
Camille says
it's gonna take some more time.

517
00:36:35.751 --> 00:36:36.960
We can't force it.

518
00:36:37.044 --> 00:36:40.088
She's been saying that
for three months now.

519
00:36:43.634 --> 00:36:44.885
She's not coming back.

520
00:36:44.968 --> 00:36:47.471
Uh. she's on her way over now.

521
00:36:48.931 --> 00:36:50.307
- What?
- She's coming this way.

522
00:36:52.267 --> 00:36:57.356
Shirley. can I. um.
just talk to you for a moment?

523
00:36:58.690 --> 00:36:59.691
[sighs]

524
00:37:00.275 --> 00:37:01.652
- [Juliette] Yeah?
- Sure.

525
00:37:02.319 --> 00:37:03.320
Um...

526
00:37:04.947 --> 00:37:08.242
Um. so Camille told me
that we used to be friends.

527
00:37:08.325 --> 00:37:11.620
We were... we were good...
good friends. right?

528
00:37:11.703 --> 00:37:13.914
- That's one way of putting it.
- Okay.

529
00:37:13.997 --> 00:37:15.332
Well. um.

530
00:37:16.875 --> 00:37:19.419
look. I don't... I don't know
who to talk to right now.

531
00:37:19.503 --> 00:37:21.421
and I... I just need...

532
00:37:23.674 --> 00:37:25.676
I had... I had a memory. right?

533
00:37:25.759 --> 00:37:27.886
I don't know if it was a dream. and I'm...

534
00:37:28.804 --> 00:37:31.640
I'm outside the air lock
with Bernard. right?

535
00:37:31.723 --> 00:37:34.893
And I get this. like.
overwhelming feeling.

536
00:37:34.977 --> 00:37:36.270
like there's something I have to do.

537
00:37:36.353 --> 00:37:38.730
and I don't know what.
but I-I know Bernard.

538
00:37:38.814 --> 00:37:43.068
He... He would've known what it was.
and. um. I think...

539
00:37:44.319 --> 00:37:45.320
I just...

540
00:37:46.864 --> 00:37:48.782
I think what I'm trying to ask you is.

541
00:37:48.866 --> 00:37:51.493
did I ever mention...
Did I say anything to you?

542
00:37:51.577 --> 00:37:54.037
- Do you know what I'm talking about?
- Um. no.

543
00:38:01.170 --> 00:38:03.422
Is she. uh... Is she looking at me?

544
00:38:04.923 --> 00:38:06.633
No. she's walking away.

545
00:38:11.889 --> 00:38:13.307
- All good?
- [Juliette] Yeah.

546
00:38:13.807 --> 00:38:14.975
Madam Mayor.

547
00:38:16.101 --> 00:38:17.102
- Excuse us.
- Sorry.

548
00:38:18.187 --> 00:38:21.857
- Orla? Yeah.
- Yes. um. there's a problem.

549
00:38:21.940 --> 00:38:25.319
and I was told I could only talk about it
with two people.

550
00:38:25.402 --> 00:38:28.822
The head of Supply and. well. you. ma'am.

551
00:38:28.906 --> 00:38:29.990
Okay.

552
00:38:30.073 --> 00:38:31.158
Um...

553
00:38:31.241 --> 00:38:32.409
- Of course. Yeah.
- Yeah.

554
00:38:34.369 --> 00:38:35.662
Critical Supply.

555
00:38:35.746 --> 00:38:38.999
Um. all the things that were loaded
in the Silo when it was built...

556
00:38:39.082 --> 00:38:41.376
Light bulbs. computers. all that...

557
00:38:41.460 --> 00:38:45.464
Well. some things.
a lot of things have gone missing.

558
00:38:45.547 --> 00:38:46.840
Maybe stolen.

559
00:38:47.716 --> 00:38:48.842
- Really?
- [Orla] Yeah.

560
00:38:48.926 --> 00:38:51.428
But I think it might
be going through construction.

561
00:38:51.512 --> 00:38:53.388
- Madam Mayor.
- Yeah?

562
00:38:54.556 --> 00:38:55.933
We have a situation.

563
00:38:57.059 --> 00:39:00.229
Security says the attackers
were wearing masks and hoods.

564
00:39:00.312 --> 00:39:01.313
Outsiders.

565
00:39:01.396 --> 00:39:03.148
What were they doing in IT?

566
00:39:03.232 --> 00:39:04.900
They took a helmet from the suit room.

567
00:39:05.609 --> 00:39:07.653
Why? Why would they take a helmet?

568
00:39:07.736 --> 00:39:08.862
Oh. shit.

569
00:39:22.543 --> 00:39:24.253
[birds chirping]

570
00:39:25.379 --> 00:39:26.505
[exhales deeply]

571
00:39:29.758 --> 00:39:31.051
[exhales deeply]

572
00:39:33.220 --> 00:39:35.639
The display is a lie.

573
00:39:39.685 --> 00:39:40.686
[exhales sharply]

574
00:39:40.769 --> 00:39:41.937
- Juliette?
- Yeah.

575
00:39:42.563 --> 00:39:43.939
Yeah. Good.

576
00:39:45.107 --> 00:39:47.109
- [Camille] Find Kennedy.
- We'll keep looking.

577
00:39:47.192 --> 00:39:49.194
Maybe if you grab one of his followers.

578
00:39:49.987 --> 00:39:51.280
Good idea.

579
00:39:58.620 --> 00:40:00.205
[phone ringing]

580
00:40:02.374 --> 00:40:03.876
- Hey.
- [Anna] <i>Hey.</i>

581
00:40:04.543 --> 00:40:07.504
Uh. your sister was shipped out
of Landstuhl 12 hours ago.

582
00:40:07.588 --> 00:40:09.798
Yeah. yeah. yeah. She's gonna land
at Andrews in ten minutes.

583
00:40:09.882 --> 00:40:11.049
I'm meeting her at Walter Reed.

584
00:40:11.133 --> 00:40:13.385
- She's not going to Walter Reed.
- What?

585
00:40:13.469 --> 00:40:15.471
<i>I'm sure you heard that her body is fine.</i>

586
00:40:15.554 --> 00:40:17.389
but she has a TBI. A traumatic...

587
00:40:17.473 --> 00:40:19.683
Traumatic brain injury.
Yeah. I know. but...

588
00:40:19.767 --> 00:40:21.977
Okay. so my-my mother
has pulled some strings.

589
00:40:22.060 --> 00:40:24.563
She's being sent
to the Heidi Stensen Clinic in Fairfax.

590
00:40:25.147 --> 00:40:27.941
<i>This is the best place for TBI
in the country.</i>

591
00:40:28.025 --> 00:40:29.443
In the world.

592
00:40:29.526 --> 00:40:31.195
The name should tell you why.

593
00:40:31.278 --> 00:40:33.113
- Oh. Stensen.
- [Anna] <i>Right.</i>

594
00:40:33.614 --> 00:40:35.032
<i>Heidi Stensen was his mother.</i>

595
00:40:35.115 --> 00:40:38.410
She had Alzheimer's.
He has sunk a lot into this facility.

596
00:40:54.676 --> 00:40:56.720
Hi. Here for Charlotte Keene.

597
00:41:22.246 --> 00:41:24.123
Well. you've looked better.

598
00:41:27.292 --> 00:41:28.502
[sighs]

599
00:41:38.512 --> 00:41:39.805
Who are you?

600
00:41:45.060 --> 00:41:47.855
We're still trying to track the Outsiders.

601
00:41:47.938 --> 00:41:50.023
Unfortunately. they're smart.

602
00:41:50.774 --> 00:41:53.819
When they split up.
they go to places there are no cameras.

603
00:41:53.902 --> 00:41:55.654
We do have this.

604
00:41:55.737 --> 00:41:58.532
- [raider] <i>Wait. Wait. stop!</i>
- [grunts. screams]

605
00:41:58.615 --> 00:42:00.033
Might've broken her wrist.

606
00:42:00.742 --> 00:42:02.161
[grunting]

607
00:42:02.244 --> 00:42:04.997
Looking for a woman
with a bandaged right arm.

608
00:42:05.080 --> 00:42:06.123
Got it.

609
00:42:21.930 --> 00:42:22.973
[Camille] What is it?

610
00:42:24.516 --> 00:42:25.851
How did I get in?

611
00:42:27.394 --> 00:42:29.229
I don't understand. What... What are you...

612
00:42:29.313 --> 00:42:31.273
How did I get through the doors?
How did I get in?

613
00:42:31.857 --> 00:42:34.318
- Well. Bernard opened them. He was...
- No. Yeah. No. no. no.

614
00:42:34.401 --> 00:42:35.611
You've said that. but I...

615
00:42:37.196 --> 00:42:39.281
I couldn't have known
that he was gonna do that.

616
00:42:40.073 --> 00:42:42.743
So. how...

617
00:42:45.037 --> 00:42:46.914
I would've had a plan. right? So. I...

618
00:42:46.997 --> 00:42:48.207
Uh...

619
00:42:49.458 --> 00:42:51.418
I would've had something. right?

620
00:42:55.881 --> 00:42:56.882
I had something.

621
00:42:59.259 --> 00:43:00.844
I had something in my hand.

622
00:43:03.013 --> 00:43:04.556
I had a crowbar.

623
00:43:04.640 --> 00:43:06.100
[distorted screams]

624
00:43:06.183 --> 00:43:08.060
And that's what I used to try
to open the doors.

625
00:43:08.644 --> 00:43:09.645
[panting]

626
00:43:10.395 --> 00:43:11.522
[grunting]

627
00:43:12.981 --> 00:43:14.399
[grunts]

628
00:43:16.151 --> 00:43:17.152
[sighs]

629
00:43:17.236 --> 00:43:18.445
[Camille] Juliette.

630
00:43:20.280 --> 00:43:21.281
Hey.

631
00:43:21.824 --> 00:43:22.991
Hey.

632
00:43:23.075 --> 00:43:24.284
Hey. look at me. Juliette.

633
00:43:24.368 --> 00:43:26.703
- [Juliette] I'm all right.
- [stammers] Juliette. listen.

634
00:43:26.787 --> 00:43:27.871
I went...

635
00:43:30.582 --> 00:43:32.084
I went into a different place.

636
00:43:32.167 --> 00:43:34.086
Yes. You did. We know this.

637
00:43:35.087 --> 00:43:36.213
I think I went...

638
00:43:37.798 --> 00:43:39.800
I think I went into another silo.

639
00:43:41.885 --> 00:43:42.886
Okay.

640
00:43:44.429 --> 00:43:46.682
I think it's time you watched it again.

641
00:43:49.435 --> 00:43:51.687
So. Bernard put cameras...

642
00:43:51.770 --> 00:43:55.107
[Juliette] In the cleaning helmets.
but he didn't show anyone. I know.

643
00:43:55.190 --> 00:43:58.026
- You told me many times.
- Right.

644
00:43:58.986 --> 00:44:00.279
- Okay.
- Yeah.

645
00:44:04.199 --> 00:44:05.659
[Camille] You remember now?

646
00:44:08.829 --> 00:44:10.164
You went outside.

647
00:44:10.247 --> 00:44:12.249
You made your way to that refuge hut.

648
00:44:12.332 --> 00:44:13.792
- You stayed in there...
- I stayed in there

649
00:44:13.876 --> 00:44:15.836
until I was strong enough to come back.

650
00:44:15.919 --> 00:44:18.046
There was a suit in there and a helmet.

651
00:44:18.755 --> 00:44:21.550
and the suit was insulated
to resist flames.

652
00:44:22.759 --> 00:44:24.094
Thank the Founders.

653
00:44:26.722 --> 00:44:27.931
Thank the Founders.

654
00:44:48.786 --> 00:44:50.621
[beeps]

655
00:44:51.872 --> 00:44:52.873
What was that?

656
00:44:53.499 --> 00:44:55.793
IT said we're low on vitamin D.

657
00:44:55.876 --> 00:44:58.921
Please ship two barrels of D+
to Water Filtration.

658
00:44:59.546 --> 00:45:01.507
- How much do they weigh?
- [Orla] Stupid amount.

659
00:45:01.590 --> 00:45:03.967
Why they have three teams. switching off.

660
00:45:04.051 --> 00:45:06.178
- They use sleds?
- They'd have to.

661
00:45:06.261 --> 00:45:07.888
That means they can only go at night.

662
00:45:08.722 --> 00:45:11.058
- They say how long it'd take?
- Three days.

663
00:45:11.683 --> 00:45:13.227
I have nothing to complain about.

664
00:45:13.310 --> 00:45:16.271
Yet. somehow you will. [chuckles]

665
00:45:19.817 --> 00:45:21.568
- [dog panting]
- How was the Council?

666
00:45:22.861 --> 00:45:25.906
It was fine. Though I had a couple run-ins
with Harwood.

667
00:45:25.989 --> 00:45:27.491
[sighs] What a dick.

668
00:45:27.574 --> 00:45:30.327
Clearly not happy with me
taking his daughter's job.

669
00:45:30.410 --> 00:45:31.870
And he knows I'm investigating her.

670
00:45:31.954 --> 00:45:33.539
She must've told him.

671
00:45:34.498 --> 00:45:35.499
[sighs]

672
00:45:36.500 --> 00:45:39.211
You know. even with everything you have
on your plate. you seem...

673
00:45:41.255 --> 00:45:43.048
I don't know.
You seem lighter than you have in weeks.

674
00:45:45.509 --> 00:45:47.261
I think it was seeing the mayor.

675
00:45:48.345 --> 00:45:53.392
Something about her just made me feel
like it's gonna be okay.

676
00:45:55.561 --> 00:45:59.314
[exhales sharply] I'm gonna go
take a look around construction.

677
00:46:00.107 --> 00:46:01.650
I saw something at the gap.

678
00:46:01.733 --> 00:46:03.986
Gave me an idea of how
she might be moving stuff.

679
00:46:04.069 --> 00:46:05.571
How?

680
00:46:05.654 --> 00:46:07.489
I'll tell you later if I'm right.

681
00:46:08.323 --> 00:46:09.575
[dog sniffing]

682
00:46:09.658 --> 00:46:11.118
- Hey.
- [laughs]

683
00:46:25.466 --> 00:46:26.592
[beeps]

684
00:46:35.017 --> 00:46:36.477
[The Algorithm] <i>How was she then?</i>

685
00:46:37.603 --> 00:46:39.313
[Camille] <i>She seemed less agitated.</i>

686
00:46:39.396 --> 00:46:42.941
I think she's fully accepted
the memory of the refuge hut as real.

687
00:46:46.862 --> 00:46:48.197
You're still concerned.

688
00:46:49.156 --> 00:46:51.325
[The Algorithm] <i>She's had no memories
for three months.</i>

689
00:46:51.408 --> 00:46:53.160
<i>other than those you've given her.</i>

690
00:46:54.036 --> 00:46:55.287
<i>And now this.</i>

691
00:46:57.623 --> 00:47:00.417
<i>The Order</i> says the memory
suppression drugs aren't perfect.

692
00:47:00.501 --> 00:47:03.587
- and that some memories will return...
<i>- We're outside</i> The Order <i>now.</i>

693
00:47:04.087 --> 00:47:07.549
<i>This isn't her recalling
a dislike for mushrooms.</i>

694
00:47:07.633 --> 00:47:11.178
<i>This is her being convinced
there's something she has to do</i>

695
00:47:12.095 --> 00:47:13.972
<i>that she just can't remember.</i>

696
00:47:15.307 --> 00:47:16.475
<i>That worries me.</i>

697
00:47:20.896 --> 00:47:21.980
<i>Double the dosage.</i>

698
00:47:30.489 --> 00:47:31.615
Your vitamins.

699
00:47:38.539 --> 00:47:40.624
The first meeting of the Silo Council.

700
00:47:40.707 --> 00:47:41.875
How was that?

701
00:47:42.584 --> 00:47:45.087
Um. I've got nothing to compare it to. so...

702
00:47:46.547 --> 00:47:49.174
- Well. I hope you sleep better tonight.
- Thanks.

703
00:47:49.258 --> 00:47:50.509
See you in the morning.

704
00:47:50.592 --> 00:47:51.593
Bye.

705
00:47:56.265 --> 00:47:57.558
- Hi.
- Hey.

706
00:47:59.143 --> 00:48:00.144
Hey. Tony.

707
00:48:01.061 --> 00:48:02.855
- [Tony] Special chowder.
- Okay.

708
00:48:02.938 --> 00:48:04.022
I hear good things.

709
00:48:05.315 --> 00:48:07.109
You say that every night. [sniffs]

710
00:48:07.192 --> 00:48:09.069
- [chuckles] I'll wait outside.
- Yeah?

711
00:48:09.153 --> 00:48:11.155
If you don't like it.
I'll get you the chicken noodle.

712
00:48:11.238 --> 00:48:12.739
All right. Thanks.

713
00:48:30.674 --> 00:48:31.967
[sighs]

714
00:48:51.320 --> 00:48:52.321
Ugh.

715
00:49:47.709 --> 00:49:48.710
Oh.

716
00:49:49.670 --> 00:49:52.256
- That bad?
- Um... Wasn't great.

717
00:49:52.798 --> 00:49:54.383
- I'll get the chicken noodle.
- No. I'm good.

718
00:49:54.466 --> 00:49:56.051
- I'm not hungry.
- Why's the bowl upside d...

719
00:49:56.135 --> 00:49:58.137
Uh. that's just to tell them
I didn't like it.

720
00:49:58.220 --> 00:50:00.013
- Loud and clear. ma'am.
- Okay. Bye. Tony.

721
00:50:00.097 --> 00:50:01.223
Bye.

722
00:50:47.686 --> 00:50:49.688
["Come Talk To Me" playing]
